  "local_port": 51826,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How should I start preparing for GSoC 2017?",
  "response": "Preparing for **Google Summer of Code (GSoC) 2017** (or any year) involves a structured approach. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide to help you get started:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Understand GSoC**\n   - **What is GSoC?** It\u2019s a global program where students contribute to open-source projects and get paid for their work.\n   - **Eligibility:** You must be 18+ and enrolled in an accredited university or college.\n   - **Timeline:** Check the [GSoC timeline](https://summerofcode.withgoogle.com/) for key dates (applications, project period, etc.).\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Explore Open-Source Organizations**\n   - Visit the [GSoC website](https://summerofcode.withgoogle.com/) and browse the list of participating organizations.\n   - Look for projects that align with your skills and interests.\n   - Check the organization\u2019s GSoC archives to see past projects and ideas.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Learn the Required Skills**\n   - Identify the programming languages, frameworks, or tools commonly used by the organizations you\u2019re interested in.\n   - If you\u2019re unfamiliar with a technology, start learning it through online courses, tutorials, or documentation.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Start Contributing**\n   - **Find Issues:** Look for beginner-friendly issues or \u201cgood first issues\u201d in the organization\u2019s repositories (e.g., on GitHub).\n   - **Submit Pull Requests:** Contribute small fixes, improvements, or documentation.\n   - **Communicate:** Join the organization\u2019s mailing list, Slack, or IRC channels to interact with mentors and other contributors.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Propose a Project**\n   - Review the organization\u2019s **Ideas List** (if available) or brainstorm your own project idea.\n   - Write a detailed **proposal** that includes:\n     - Problem statement\n     - Proposed solution\n     - Timeline of tasks\n     - Your relevant skills and experience\n   - Get feedback from mentors or the community before submitting.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Prepare for the Application**\n   - **Research:** Understand the organization\u2019s expectations and read past successful proposals.\n   - **Polish Your Resume:** Highlight your open-source contributions, technical skills, and relevant projects.\n   - **Practice Coding:** Prepare for potential technical interviews or coding exercises.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Stay Organized**\n   - Use a planner or spreadsheet to track deadlines, tasks, and progress.\n   - Follow the organization\u2019s guidelines for submissions and communications.\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Submit Your Application**\n   - Submit your application through the GSoC website before the deadline.\n   - Ensure your proposal is clear, concise, and well-structured.\n\n---\n\n### 9. **Stay Active**\n   - Continue contributing to the organization even after submitting your application.\n   - Demonstrate your enthusiasm and commitment to the project.\n\n---\n\n### Additional Tips:\n   - **Be Patient:** Open-source contributions take time, and mentors may be busy.\n   - **Network:** Connect with other GSoC aspirants and past participants for advice and support.\n   - **Stay Updated:** Follow GSoC announcements and organization updates.\n\n---\n\nGood luck with your GSoC journey! Start early and stay consistent\u2014your efforts will pay off!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
